[% META
   title = "File Upload Behavior — How Files Get to Disk and Database"
   description = "Explains exactly what each upload method does to disk and the files database table"
   roles = "admin"
   TemplateType = "Documentation"
   category = "FileManagement"
   page_version = "0.01"
   last_updated = "2026-03-02"
%]
[% PageVersion = 'Documentation/FileUploadBehavior.tt,v 0.01 2026/03/02 AI Exp AI ' %]
[% IF debug_mode == 1 %]
  [% PageVersion %]
[% END %]

<div class="app-container">

  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>File Upload Behavior</h1>
    <p>How files get to disk and into the database — by upload method</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-container">
    <div class="content-primary">

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Overview</h2>
        <p>
          The file management system has <strong>three distinct ways</strong> a file can be registered.
          Each method has different behaviour regarding what it writes to disk and what it records in the
          <code>files</code> database table. Understanding which method does what is critical to
          avoiding orphaned disk files or orphaned database records.
        </p>

        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:14px">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Method</th>
              <th>Writes to Disk?</th>
              <th>Creates DB Record?</th>
              <th>Duplicate Check?</th>
              <th>Who can use it?</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>upload_file</strong> — Upload page form</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately after disk write</td>
              <td>Yes (name + size)</td>
              <td>Admin (SiteName or CSC)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>fs_upload_tree</strong> — Admin Browser "Upload" button / drag-drop</td>
              <td>Yes — each file as it arrives</td>
              <td><strong>No</strong></td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Admin (SiteName or CSC)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>db_import_file</strong> — "+DB" button in Admin Browser</td>
              <td><strong>No</strong> — file must already be on disk</td>
              <td>Yes</td>
              <td>Yes (name + size + SHA256)</td>
              <td>Admin (SiteName or CSC)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Method 1 — Upload Page Form (<code>/file/upload_file</code>)</h2>
        <p>Accessed via the <em>Upload File</em> menu item. This is the traditional single-file upload.</p>
        <h3>Step-by-step</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Admin selects a file and chooses a target NFS directory from the dropdown.</li>
          <li>
            The server resolves the physical NFS path for that allocation record
            (e.g. <code>/mnt/nfs/CSC</code>).
            CSC admin can also type a raw directory path directly.
          </li>
          <li>The file is <strong>written to disk</strong> at <code>{nfs_path}/{filename}</code>.</li>
          <li>
            The <code>files</code> table is checked for an existing record with the same
            <strong>name and size</strong>. If a match is found, <code>is_duplicate = 1</code>
            and <code>duplicate_of</code> is set to the matching record's ID.
          </li>
          <li>A new row is <strong>inserted into the <code>files</code> table</strong> with
              <code>source_type = 'upload'</code>, the detected MIME type, and
              the full disk path in both <code>file_path</code> and <code>nfs_path</code>.
          </li>
          <li>
            If the database insert <strong>fails</strong>, the file that was just written to disk is
            <strong>deleted</strong> (rollback). An error is shown in the browser.
          </li>
          <li>On success the admin is redirected to the File List page.</li>
        </ol>
        <p style="background:#e8f5e9;border-left:4px solid #43a047;padding:8px 12px;border-radius:3px">
          <strong>Result:</strong> File appears on disk AND in the database simultaneously.
          You will see it in the Admin Browser and in the File List immediately.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Method 2 — Admin Browser Upload / Drag-Drop (<code>/file/fs_upload_tree</code>)</h2>
        <p>
          Accessed via the <em>Upload</em> button in the Admin Browser, or by dragging files/folders
          onto the browser panel. This is an AJAX endpoint — the browser sends one HTTP request per file.
        </p>
        <h3>Step-by-step</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Admin selects files or a directory tree in the browser's file picker (or drags them in).</li>
          <li>
            The browser JavaScript sends each file individually to the server with its
            <strong>relative path</strong> preserved (so subdirectories are recreated).
          </li>
          <li>
            The server checks that the target directory is within the admin's allowed NFS allocation
            (CSC admin can use any existing directory; SiteName admin is restricted to their allocation).
          </li>
          <li>
            Missing subdirectories are created automatically with <code>make_path</code>.
          </li>
          <li>Each file is <strong>written to disk</strong>. The server returns <code>{"ok":1}</code>.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>No database record is created.</strong> The file exists only on disk until
            you explicitly add it to the database.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="background: var(--caution-bg, #fff3e0);border-left:4px solid #fb8c00;padding:8px 12px;border-radius:3px">
          <strong>Result:</strong> Files appear in the Admin Browser directory listing immediately
          (because the browser reads the filesystem). They do <strong>NOT</strong> appear in the
          File List or Duplicates pages until you use the "+DB" button or the "Dir Sync" feature
          to import them into the database.
        </p>

        <h3>Directory uploads</h3>
        <p>
          When a folder is selected (or dragged), the browser sends every file with its path relative
          to the folder root. The server recreates the full subdirectory tree under the target directory.
          All files land on disk in one operation. Again — no DB records are created during this step.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Method 3 — "+DB" Button (<code>/file/db_import_file</code>)</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>+DB</strong> button appears next to each file in the Admin Browser.
          Use it to register an existing on-disk file in the database.
        </p>
        <h3>Step-by-step</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Admin clicks <strong>+DB</strong> next to a file in the Admin Browser.</li>
          <li>The server verifies the file actually exists on disk at that path.</li>
          <li>
            If the file is <strong>already in the <code>files</code> table</strong>
            (matched by <code>file_path</code> or <code>nfs_path</code>), the admin is redirected
            to the edit page for that record so they can update its attributes.
            No duplicate record is created.
          </li>
          <li>
            If the file is <strong>not yet in the database</strong>:
            <ul>
              <li>A SHA256 hash of the file's content is computed.</li>
              <li>
                The <code>files</code> table is checked for a matching hash (or name+size as fallback).
                If found, <code>is_duplicate = 1</code> and <code>duplicate_of</code> is set.
              </li>
              <li>
                A new DB record is created with <code>source_type = 'nfs'</code>, the SHA256 hash
                stored in <code>file_hash</code>, and the current admin's SiteName / session data.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Admin is redirected back to the Admin Browser directory they were in.</li>
        </ol>
        <p style="background:#e8f5e9;border-left:4px solid #43a047;padding:8px 12px;border-radius:3px">
          <strong>Result:</strong> File was already on disk; now it also has a database record.
          It will appear in the File List and Duplicates pages.
          The disk file is not touched or moved.
        </p>
        <p style="background:#fde8e8;border-left:4px solid #e53935;padding:8px 12px;border-radius:3px;margin-top:8px">
          <strong>Warning:</strong> Computing the SHA256 hash reads the entire file. For very large
          files this can take several seconds and will block the server (single-threaded dev mode)
          during that time. On large directories use <em>Dir Sync</em> instead, which defers
          hash computation to import time and caps the scan at 2000 files.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Dir Sync — Bulk Import (<code>/file/dir_sync</code>)</h2>
        <p>
          The <em>Dir Sync</em> button (in the Admin Browser toolbar) is the recommended way to
          import many files from an existing NFS directory into the database in one pass.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>Admin clicks <strong>Dir Sync</strong> for a directory.</li>
          <li>
            The server scans the directory (non-recursive by default; check the box for recursive,
            capped at 2000 files to prevent hangs).
          </li>
          <li>
            Each file is classified as <em>New</em>, <em>Duplicate</em> (name+size match),
            <em>Already in DB</em>, or <em>Proxmox/system file</em> — using fast DB queries only
            (no SHA256 at scan time).
          </li>
          <li>Admin reviews the table and selects which files to import (or skip).</li>
          <li>
            On submit, only the files marked <em>Import</em> are processed:
            SHA256 is computed now, a DB record is created, and the duplicate flag is set if needed.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <p style="background:#e8f5e9;border-left:4px solid #43a047;padding:8px 12px;border-radius:3px">
          <strong>Result:</strong> Selected files gain DB records; skipped files remain disk-only.
          Nothing is moved or deleted.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Summary — When Will I See the File?</h2>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Where you look</th>
              <th>upload_file</th>
              <th>fs_upload_tree (Admin Browser upload)</th>
              <th>+DB button</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Admin Browser directory listing</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately</td>
              <td>Was already visible</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>File List (<code>/file/list</code>)</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately</td>
              <td>No — must +DB or Dir Sync first</td>
              <td>Yes — immediately</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Duplicates page</td>
              <td>Yes — if duplicate detected</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Yes — if duplicate detected</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Workshop file picker</td>
              <td>Yes (if access_level allows)</td>
              <td>No</td>
              <td>Yes (if access_level allows)</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section">
        <h2>Access Control Summary</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>CSC Admin</strong> — can upload to any existing directory on the NFS, or type a raw path. No allocation needed.</li>
          <li><strong>SiteName Admin</strong> — can only upload into directories that CSC admin has allocated to their SiteName via NFS Allocations. They cannot navigate above their allocation root.</li>
          <li><strong>Regular users</strong> — cannot use any upload or browser functions. They interact with files only through application features (e.g. Workshop file picker).</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>

</div>
